readUrlSegments() returns false when the number of segments are not of the same size.  We can't use it for this situation where we only need to match the first 3 or 4 segments of "thisUrl".  I'm guessing we'd want to make a duplicate function that attempts to match only the first X segments of a URL?
Yep, I realized that last night;  There's a fix coming momentarily.

Then we also need to detect when we're in an action.  (probably by looking for ActionInfo + target as the type.

I don't think we can just parse all strings as URIs and if they parse, assume they need aggregated.  That leaves a lot to chance.

> Then we also need to detect when we're in an action.  (probably by looking for ActionInfo + target as the type.
Actions aren't the only one.  I've seen some sort of "protects" field under ComponentIntegrity that contains a URI and I wouldn't be surprised if there are other ones hidden in the schema.  Trying to maintain a complete list would be a headache.


> I don't think we can just parse all strings as URIs and if they parse, assume they need aggregated.  That leaves a lot to chance.But in this instance we're only parsing URIs that exist on the satellite BMC so there isn't a risk of overwriting a URI that actually points to a location on the aggregating BMC.

We perform the same matching here that we do in determining if we need to forward a request to the satellite BMC.  Worst case scenario, we're messing up the same edge cases here that we mess up when determining the initial routing.  

I think we can use the proper solution to the initial aggregation check here as well where eventually we'll be able to build a list of aggregateable URIs at runtime from the schema files.  We can use that same information here to determine if we need to add the prefix to any string that's parsable as a URI.  That way we don't have to worry about checking for specific keys.

> > Then we also need to detect when we're in an action.  (probably by looking for ActionInfo + target as the type.
> Actions aren't the only one.  I've seen some sort of "protects" field under ComponentIntegrity that contains a URI and I wouldn't be surprised if there are other ones hidden in the schema.  Trying to maintain a complete list would be a headache.

ComponentsProtected is what I'm assuming you mean there?  Those are going to be NavigationReference types, so they'll have an odata.id key, so they should be caught by this check.

I think Actions is the only weird one, and only because it drops outside the redfish resource tree.  You're right, I don't want to maintain a full list, but I also don't want to try parsing every string as URI, as it opens us up to possible attack vectors.  For example, what if I put a valid URL in a manufacturer field in a FRU?  This would try to aggregate it.

> 
> 
> > I don't think we can just parse all strings as URIs and if they parse, assume they need aggregated.  That leaves a lot to chance.But in this instance we're only parsing URIs that exist on the satellite BMC so there isn't a risk of overwriting a URI that actually points to a location on the aggregating BMC.
> 
> We perform the same matching here that we do in determining if we need to forward a request to the satellite BMC.

The difference is we do it on the URI of the payload, that we KNOW is a URI.  This is trying to do it on every string field in the system, of which some are very likely to parse as valid URIs.

>  Worst case scenario, we're messing up the same edge cases here that we mess up when determining the initial routing.  
> 
> I think we can use the proper solution to the initial aggregation check here as well where eventually we'll be able to build a list of aggregateable URIs at runtime from the schema files.  We can use that same information here to determine if we need to add the prefix to any string that's parsable as a URI.  That way we don't have to worry about checking for specific keys.

I think it's simpler than that, but the above would work too.

> ComponentsProtected is what I'm assuming you mean there?  Those are going to be NavigationReference types, so they'll have an odata.id key, so they should be caught by this check.
You're right, I was misremembering.  The property is "TargetComponentURI" which is a property of ComponentIntegrity.  There is also the Task property "TargetUri".  There could be others as well.  We could look to fix "@odata.id", "TargetComponentURI", "TargetUri", and any strings under "Actions".

> I don't want to maintain a full list, but I also don't want to try parsing every string as URI
I completely agree.  However, I think we need to do one of those two options at least for now.

> but I also don't want to try parsing every string as URI, as it opens us up to possible attack vectors.  For example, what if I put a valid URL in a manufacturer field in a FRU?  This would try to aggregate it.
We're not aggregating it though, we're just modifying the URL that gets returned to the user.  If an attacker put a valid URL in the manufacturer field in a FRU then we'd still return that as part of the response even if we don't add a prefix to it.

> The difference is we do it on the URI of the payload, that we KNOW is a URI.  This is trying to do it on every string field in the system, of which some are very likely to parse as valid URIs.
What if we make sure the first two segments are "redfish" and "v1" on top of checking if it parses as a valid URI?  That should prevent us from modifying strings that aren't actually Redfish URIs.

> > ComponentsProtected is what I'm assuming you mean there?  Those are going to be NavigationReference types, so they'll have an odata.id key, so they should be caught by this check.
> You're right, I was misremembering.  The property is "TargetComponentURI" which is a property of ComponentIntegrity.  There is also the Task property "TargetUri".  There could be others as well.  We could look to fix "@odata.id", "TargetComponentURI", "TargetUri", and any strings under "Actions".

The thought that just came to my head was can we do case-insensitive .ends_with("Uri"), and does that cover most or all of the cases?

Other idea, in theory, any URI is going to start with /redfish/v1..... that's far less brittle if we did that check, although still attackable, although I'm not sure how bad the impact would be.

> 
> > I don't want to maintain a full list, but I also don't want to try parsing every string as URI
> I completely agree.  However, I think we need to do one of those two options at least for now.
> 
> > but I also don't want to try parsing every string as URI, as it opens us up to possible attack vectors.  For example, what if I put a valid URL in a manufacturer field in a FRU?  This would try to aggregate it.

> 
> > The difference is we do it on the URI of the payload, that we KNOW is a URI.  This is trying to do it on every string field in the system, of which some are very likely to parse as valid URIs.
> What if we make sure the first two segments are "redfish" and "v1" on top of checking if it parses as a valid URI?  That should prevent us from modifying strings that aren't actually Redfish URIs.

> The thought that just came to my head was can we do case-insensitive .ends_with("Uri"), and does that cover most or all of the cases?
I think that will cover most cases if we do that in addition to "@odata.id", "target" and anything under "Actions".  I see "target" appear in a large number of schemas so I can't be sure they will only appear under "Actions".

> Other idea, in theory, any URI is going to start with /redfish/v1..... that's far less brittle if we did that check, although still attackable, although I'm not sure how bad the impact would be.
I think this would work as well.  I'm also still not seeing how this is an attack concern.  Or at least how it only becomes a vulnerability if we apply a prefix.

> > The thought that just came to my head was can we do case-insensitive .ends_with("Uri"), and does that cover most or all of the cases?
> I think that will cover most cases if we do that in addition to "@odata.id", "target" and anything under "Actions".  I see "target" appear in a large number of schemas so I can't be sure they will only appear under "Actions".
> 
> > Other idea, in theory, any URI is going to start with /redfish/v1..... that's far less brittle if we did that check, although still attackable, although I'm not sure how bad the impact would be.
> I think this would work as well.  I'm also still not seeing how this is an attack concern.  Or at least how it only becomes a vulnerability if we apply a prefix.

We've had instances before of people putting things like links in the field of an IPMI FRU, which then gets formatted, and turned into a link that the user could click on (or worse, injects some script).  It's pretty possible it's less of a concern in this case, and requiring it start with redfish/v1 SEVERELY limits what you could even potentially do with it, so I might be ok with that, although I like the explicitness of the "target + actions + odata.id" approach.

IDK, I'm on the fence.

> We've had instances before of people putting things like links in the field of an IPMI FRU, which then gets formatted, and turned into a link that the user could click on (or worse, injects some script).  
I don't think that issue is addressed if we restrict the fields that we can attempt to add prefixes to.  An attacker could still change FRUs to include a malicious URI and we'd return it since we're just forwarding the satellite's response to the user.

> It's pretty possible it's less of a concern in this case, and requiring it start with redfish/v1 SEVERELY limits what you could even potentially do with it, so I might be ok with that, although I like the explicitness of the "target + actions + odata.id" approach.
The latter is fine, we might just have to hotfix later if it turns out we missed an edge case.  My preference is the former so we don't have to worry about that.
